## What happened

In **.NET 11**, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (and any DSA sign/verify operation) now throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. DSA still works on Windows and Linux.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy signatures** (not create new ones), you have two options:

**Option 1 – Platform-guard DSA calls** (if you must keep verifying old DSA signatures):

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
        "DSA signature verification is not supported on macOS with .NET 11+.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**Option 2 – Migrate to ECDSA/RSA** (recommended long-term):

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var sig = ecdsa.SignData(data, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

This requires re-signing data with the new algorithm, so it's a larger change but eliminates the legacy dependency entirely.

**Bottom line:** If macOS support is required and you can't re-sign, run DSA verification only on Windows/Linux and add a runtime guard. Long-term, migrate to **ECDSA** or **RSA**.
